    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-04-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-04-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="251"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d251">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/4–1951</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Director of the Office of Northeast Asian
                        Affairs</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for
                        Far Eastern Affairs</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Merchant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-04-20">April 20,
                            1951</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Subject: Alleged Bombing Attack on China Coast near Shanghai</p>
                <p>With reference to New York’s 1425, April 19, concerning Rau’s report that
                    Panikkar had reported from Peiping that an air attack had been made on the China
                    coast by US bombers, I talked to Admiral Thach<note n="1" xml:id="d251fn1">Rear
                        Adm. James H. Thach, Director, International Affairs, Office of the Deputy
                        Chief of Naval Operations.</note> in the Navy regarding the possibility of
                    planes from the 7th Fleet on its recent sweep along the south China coast having
                    accidentally bombed Chinese territory.<note n="2" xml:id="d251fn2">See footnote
                        2, <ref target="#pg_298">p. 298</ref>.</note> Admiral Thach immediately sent
                    a radio to <gloss target="#t_COMNAVFE1">COMNAVFE</gloss> which replied that no
                    bombing of any kind took place and none could have as none of the planes carried
                    any bombs whatever and not a shot was fired by any of the planes.</p>
                <p>I informed Mr. Hickerson of the foregoing in order that a categorical denial
                    could be made to Rau. I agreed with Admiral Thach that no public statement in
                    this regard would be made without prior clearance with the Navy.</p>
            </div>
